<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Gibb River Road</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Gibb River Road</h2><p><i>Western Australia · Kimberley region, Derby to Kununurra</i></p><p><b>660 km of red-dirt corrugations across the Kimberley — gorges, boab trees, isolation, 4WD essential.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>710 km (441 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>5–10 days minimum</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>May–September dry season only (the road is closed by floods Nov–Apr most years)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Corrugated gravel that destroys vehicles; river crossings (some tidal); no fuel for hundreds of km; saltwater crocodiles in tidal rivers; remoteness; satphone strongly recommended</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>860</td></tr></table><hr><p>The Gibb is the great Australian outback drive — an unsealed cattle road built in the 1960s through the heart of the Kimberley to truck beef from remote stations to the ports. It became famous as a tourist route in the 1980s. 4WD only; you'll want two spares, a UHF radio, and ideally a sat-phone. The road is closed half the year by Wet Season floods. What you get for the trouble: gorges that the Imintji and Worrorra peoples have known for fifty thousand years (Bell, Galvans, Manning, Mitchell), boab trees that look like upended root systems, and a Kimberley sky at night with no light pollution within hundreds of kilometres. Filling the fuel tank at Mount Barnett or Drysdale is essential — the next pump may be 300 km on.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Windjana Gorge</b> — Devonian limestone gorge — a 350 million-year-old fossil reef from when this country was tropical sea floor. Freshwater crocodiles bask on the sandbanks; safe to walk past at distance.</li><li><b>Tunnel Creek</b> — 750 m natural tunnel cut through the same limestone reef. Wade through with a torch; bats roosting overhead. Hideout of Jandamarra, the Bunuba resistance leader killed by police in 1897.</li><li><b>Bell Gorge</b> — Iconic Kimberley swimming hole — multi-tier waterfall into a cliff-walled pool. 1 km walk in from the parking area. Best around 10am for sun on the water.</li><li><b>Manning Gorge</b> — Reached by an ankle-deep creek crossing and a 2.5 km hike. Big swimming pool below a 30 m waterfall. The cattle station here (Mount Barnett, run by the Kupungarri Aboriginal community) sells fuel and supplies.</li><li><b>Mitchell Falls (Punamii-Uunpuu)</b> — Four-tier waterfall in remote Mitchell Plateau country — a long detour up the Kalumburu Road, 4WD high-clearance only. Helicopter flights from the airstrip. Sacred site for Wunambal Gaambera people.</li><li><b>Pentecost River crossing</b> — Tidal crossing — saltwater crocodiles are present. Time the crossing for low water; check depth on foot before driving. The Cockburn Range fills the horizon behind you.</li><li><b>El Questro / Emma Gorge</b> — Million-acre cattle station turned wilderness park. Emma Gorge is a 1.5 km walk to a fern-curtained pool with a thermal warm spring on its eastern wall. Sunrise/sunset chairlifts in the property's gorges.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
